NAME
       file - determine file type

SYNOPSIS
       file [OPTION...] [FILE...]

DESCRIPTION
       Determine  type  of  FILEs  by  examining  their  contents  using
       magic number tests, text encoding heuristics, and language
       detection.

OPTIONS
       -b, --brief
              do not prepend filenames to output lines

       -E     on filesystem errors, issue an error message and exit

       -f, --files-from=FILE
              read the filenames to be examined from FILE (one per line);
              use - for standard input

       -F, --separator=STRING
              use STRING as separator instead of ": "

       -h, --no-dereference
              don't follow symlinks

       -i, --mime
              output MIME type strings (type and encoding)

       --mime-type
              output the MIME type only

       --mime-encoding
              output the MIME encoding only

       -k, --keep-going
              don't stop at the first match

       -L, --dereference
              follow symlinks (default)

       -N, --no-pad
              don't pad output

       -r, --raw
              don't translate unprintable chars to \ooo

       -s, --special-files
              treat special (device) files as ordinary files

       -v, --version
              output version information and exit

       -0, --print0
              output NUL after filename

       --help display this help and exit

DETAILS
       The file command performs several tests in order: magic number
       tests (ELF analysis, archive formats, images, scripts), then
       text/encoding heuristics (UTF-8, ASCII), then programming
       language detection (C, C++, Python, shell, Java), then falls
       back to "data" for binary files.

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      if errors occurred

